\"MiniMax-M2.7\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775555029933,\n      \"responseId\": \"062404d607dbb2d48d890ef6ec730308\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"58c72871\",\n        \"seq\": 744\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Let me poll it.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_function_8enzdcjotp6m_1\",\n          \"name\": \"process\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"action\": \"poll\",\n            \"sessionId\": \"swift-nexus\",\n            \"timeout\": 90000\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n      \"provider\": \"minimax-portal\",\n      \"model\": \"MiniMax-M2.7\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775555095817,\n      \"responseId\": \"06240518d2023b5beffadad0a695a029\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"de3fa253\",\n        \"seq\": 746\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"The push function is working, but there's an error with the Feishu API: `HTTP 400: {\\\"code\\\":99992361,\\\"msg\\\":\\\"open_id cross app\\\",\\\"error\\\":...}`. \\n\\nThis means the `open_id` we're using (`ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae`) is for a different app. The app_id/app_secret being used is for the OpenClaw app, but the open_id was configured for a different Feishu app integration.\\n\\nThis is a configuration issue with the Feishu push module. The open_id is hardcoded in `_load_feishu_config()` in `feishu_push.py`. \\n\\nThe `open_id` belongs to the OpenClaw Feishu app, but we're trying to use it with a different app's credentials. When sending messages via the OpenClaw Feishu webhook, I need to either use the correct open_id for that app or switch to using the OpenClaw channel instead. I should check how other push scripts in the project handle this.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"推送逻辑跑通了，但飞书 API 鉴权有问题——`open_id cross app` 说明用的是 OpenClaw 的 app credentials，但 open_id 是另一个 App 的。需要用 OpenClaw 自己的 channel 来发消息：\\n\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_function_mrzcbcwj7zye_1\",\n          \"name\": \"exec\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"command\": \"grep -n \\\"open_id\\\\|_load_feishu_config\\\" ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/feishu_push.py\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n      \"provider\": \"minimax-portal\",\n      \"model\": \"MiniMax-M2.7\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775555113278,\n      \"responseId\": \"0624052911033f1eb5cc678d3d7e3905\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"fcd314d0\",\n        \"seq\": 748\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"The `open_id` is hardcoded as `ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` (张玲). This is the user's OpenClaw account, but the Feishu app credentials are different. The issue is that the app_id/app_secret are from the OpenClaw Feishu app, but the open_id is for the user from a different Feishu app integration.\\n\\nFor OpenClaw's own Feishu channel, I should use the OpenClaw message tool to send the message instead of calling the Feishu API directly. The `message` tool in the OpenClaw toolbox can send Feishu messages.\\n \\nSo the real problem is that when I try to send directly to the user's open_id through the Feishu API, it fails because that open_id belongs to a different app context. But when I use OpenClaw's built-in Feishu integration with the `message` tool, OpenClaw handles the proper authentication and routing. I could rewrite `_push_candidate_change` to use the `message` tool instead of making direct API calls.\\n\\nThe tricky part is that the `message` tool needs a channel identifier and target—the `channel` parameter for Feishu is typically \\\"feishu\\\" with the user's open_id or chat_id as the target. I need to figure out what channel name the OpenClaw Feishu plugin actually registers under, since the plugin seems to integrate Feishu into OpenClaw's own channel system rather than exposing the raw Feishu API.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"这个 Feishu API 是 OpenClaw 自己的 app，但 `open_id` 跨 App 了。最简单的方式是直接用 OpenClaw 的 `message` 工具推送给张玲，不需要自己调 API：\\n\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_function_fus2wpqfetk5_1\",\n          \"name\": \"exec\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"command\": \"grep -n \\\"open_id\\\\|_load_feishu_config\\\\|send_card\\\\|send_message\\\" ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/feishu_push.py | head -20\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n      \"provider\": \"minimax-portal\",\n      \"model\": \"MiniMax-M2.7\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775555123987,\n      \"responseId\": \"06240534a44c2402f93b68b1a4881d32\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"4aed4683\",\n        \"seq\": 750\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"I need to update the `_push_candidate_change` function to use the OpenClaw `message` tool instead of calling the Feishu API directly. The `message` tool can send messages to Feishu using OpenClaw's built-in channel integration.\\n\\nBut this is tricky because the function is called from within the Python script, not from here. I need to find a way to invoke the `message` tool from within the script, OR modify the approach.\\n\\nOne approach: Instead of calling `_send_feishu_message` directly, the script could write the push content to a file, and then have a separate mechanism trigger the OpenClaw message tool.\\n\\n\\nI'm realizing there are a few options here: I could write to a temp file and have a separate script trigger the message, use OpenClaw's Python API directly, or just fix the root cause by getting the right credentials. Let me look more carefully at what `_load_feishu_config` is actually doing.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_function_jdan2z3jcyh6_1\",\n          \"name\": \"exec\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"command\": \"sed -n '18,30p' ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/feishu_push.py\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n      \"provider\": \"minimax-portal\",\n      \"model\": \"MiniMax-M2.7\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775555138508,\n      \"responseId\": \"06240542e67fc90c6ed8438b42a298fb\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"a1cda1ad\",\n        \"seq\": 752\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"The issue is that the `app_id`/`app_secret` in `openclaw.json` belong to OpenClaw's Feishu app, but the `open_id` belongs to the user who was added to a different Feishu app. The user was added to the OpenClaw Feishu app as a member, so the open_id should be valid for OpenClaw's app.\\n\\nActually, wait. The error is \\\"open_id cross app\\\" which means the open_id doesn't belong to the app whose credentials are being used. This means the open_id in the config IS correct for OpenClaw's app, but there's some other issue.\\n \\nLooking at the error more carefully—`{\\\"code\\\":99992361,\\\"msg\\\":\\\"open_id cross app\\\"}`—this typically means the user isn't part of the Feishu app or the wrong app credentials are being used. But the open_id is hardcoded in the config, so maybe there's a mismatch between which app credentials are actually being loaded versus what the open_id expects.\\n\\nThe simplest fix would be to bypass the Feishu API entirely and use OpenClaw's own message tool instead, which already handles the correct OpenClaw app integration. Since the `message` tool is an agent-level tool and not directly callable from a script, I'd need to write the message to a file and have a separate OpenClaw process pick it up, or use a shell command to trigger it.\\n\\nActually, I could write the push content to a dedicated file and configure a cron job or heartbeat to monitor it and send messages via the message tool when new content appears. But the most straightforward approach is to fix the Feishu API credentials directly—I should use the correct app_id and app_secret from the OpenClaw channel configuration stored in `openclaw.json`, which should be the same ones the Feishu plugin uses for the webhook.\\n\\nLet me check what Feishu configuration is actually stored in openclaw.json to get the right credentials.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_function_shdpn3moh7ry_1\",\n          \"name\": \"exec\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"command\": \"python3 -c \\\"\\nimport json\\nfrom pathlib import Path\\ncfg = json.loads(Path.home().joinpath('.openclaw/openclaw.json').read_text())\\nfeishu = cfg.get('channels', {}).get('feishu', {})\\nprint('feishu keys:', list(feishu.keys()))\\naccounts = feishu.get('accounts', {})\\nfor k,v in accounts.items():\\n    print(f'account {k}: appId={v.get(\\\\\\\"appId\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\")[:20]}... openId={v.get(\\\\\\\"openId\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\")}')\\n\\\"\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n      \"provider\": \"minimax-portal\",\n      \"model\": \"MiniMax-M2.7\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775555147381,\n      \"responseId\": \"0624054b9c13a88c55bd917e124d5e4b\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"cfc9b800\",\n        \"seq\": 754\n      }\n    }\n  ],\n  \"truncated\": true,\n  \"droppedMessages\": false,\n  \"contentTruncated\": true,\n  \"contentRedacted\": false,\n  \"bytes\": 32752\n}"}],"details":{"sessionKey":"agent:coding-agent:subagent:280404ff-bedc-4b66-b49d-83b5ff5e0df5","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still not right. `compute_candidate_snapshot` is at line 612 but `if __name__` is at 670. Let me check where `main()` is defined."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1n3kiq1r35hz_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"^def \\|^if __name__\" ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775554646421,"responseId":"06240356b7308b32982545c39cce9df7","__openclaw":{"id":"5a27fa0c","seq":706}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So:\n- `main()` is at line 484\n- Helper functions are at lines 612-647\n- `if __name__` is at line 670\n\nThe issue is that Python doesn't care about line order for function definitions in terms of `main()` calling them - as long as the functions are defined BEFORE they are CALLED. Since the call to `compute_candidate_snapshot` is inside `main()`, and `main()` is called at line 671 (`main()`), by the time `main()` runs, all functions (including those at 612-647) will have been defined because Python parses the whole module first.\n\nWait... but the error said `name 'compute_candidate_snapshot' is not defined`. \n\nOh, I see the actual problem now. The `compute_candidate_snapshot` function is defined after `if __name__ == \"__main__\":` at line 612, but `main()` is called at line 671 inside that block. When Python parses the file, it executes code sequentially, so `main()` gets called before the function at line 612 is ever defined.\n\nActually, wait - that's not how Python works. All function definitions get parsed first regardless of order, so `compute_candidate_snapshot` should be available to `main()` even though it appears later in the file. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_oqrz6ugveekz_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -m py_compile ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py && echo \"Syntax OK\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775554650072,"responseId":"0624035a805215bd133e02eb92d634dd","__openclaw":{"id":"0af0b054","seq":708}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ah, there's a syntax error! The `snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\n\")` line got mangled. The `\\n` at the end of the heredoc in the original `cat >>` command was interpreted as a newline by the shell. Let me look at what's happening at line 643."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mz98108b25qz_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"sed -n '638,650p' ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775554660691,"responseId":"062403652f981e9417c0002d4748155d","__openclaw":{"id":"1c37a056","seq":710}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Line 644 has a syntax error. The `\"+\"` line is broken - the string continuation got split. It should be:\n```python\nsnap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\n\", encoding=\"utf-8\")\n```\n\nBut it got written as:\n```python\nsnap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\n\", encoding=\"utf-8\")\n```\n\nThe `\"\\n\"` from the heredoc was interpreted as an actual newline, splitting the string. Let me fix this."},{"type":"text","text":"\n语法错误——heredoc 的 `\\n` 被当成真实换行符了。修复：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_eydorocl1qrl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - << 'PYEOF'\npath = \"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py\"\nwith open(path) as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\n# Fix the broken string continuation in save_snapshot\nold = 'snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\n\"'\nfixed = 'snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\\\n\"'\ncontent = content.replace(\n    'snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\n\"',\n    'snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\\\n\"'\n)\n# Also fix the one that was split across lines\ncontent = content.replace(\n    'snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\n\", encoding=\"utf-8\")',\n    'snap_file.write_text(json.dumps(snapshot, ensure_ascii=False) + \"\\\\n\", encoding=\"utf-8\")'\n)\nwith open(path, \"w\") as f:\n    f.write(content)\nprint(\"Fixed\")\nPYEOF"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775554665355,"responseId":"06240369d43c0675a6be86b166479f99","__openclaw":{"id":"58ea57c4","seq":712}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me verify the fix and check syntax."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nikzvbjjp9a8_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -m py_compile ~/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py && echo \"Syntax OK\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stopReason":"toolUse"